		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">Twin buildings are a generalisation of spherical buildings in the same way that Kac-Moody groups are a generalisation of Chevalley groups. The well-known results of Tits on spherical buildings have been generalised to twin buildings by Muhlherr and Ronan [MR], but there are some complications. The major theorem for spherical buildings shows that the local (rank 2) structure determines the global structure has been proved for 2-spherical twin buildings (meaning the rank 2 residues are spherical), except in certain  fragile  cases. However, it appears that in some of these cases the Local to Global theorem is false. On the other hand there seem to be some cases that are not 2-spherical, but in which Local to Global remains true.In March 2001, Ronan and Muhlherr both visited Belgium at the same time and their discussions led to a new notion of  panel-connectedness  that they believe will solve this problem: when it holds the local structure should determine the global structure, and when it fails the twin buildings should prove to be rather wild.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
